default“reasonable”
default rates of expenditure on hi
defaults fully-justified defence
default (as used to be the case)
default.
default The likelihood is that some defendants will be compelled to employ no lawyers or only the very most junior to conduct even complicated cases where they cannot afford to spend money on experienced advocate
defaults when there is no prospect of recovering fees that may be reasonable but nonetheless would be in excess of legal aid rates.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf cuts are imposed on advocates it would be right that the issue of time of payment be considered, as well as travelling expenses
default. For many junior barristers (and a growing number of more senior ones also) the costs of travel may outweigh the full gross fee for a case. The local Bar rule is no longer fit for use, and should be replaced by payment of the reasonable travel costs of al
defaultl advocates attending court so that at least the individual is not actually out-of-pocket for having agreed to go to work (or meet professional obligations to attend in relation to a case transferred to follow a judge to another court).
default In addition the unc
defaultertainty over timing of payment for a case
default, as to when it may conclude, or the fee be processed by the LAA is a major problem when fees are so low in any event. 
